quantityType.name: absorbed dose
quantityType.description: Radiation Absorbed Dose is a physical dose quantity representing the mean energy imparted to matter per unit mass by ionizing radiation. The SI unit for this quantity is Gray (Gy). @see Wikipedia: Absorbed Dose

quantityType.name: acceleration
amount of substance
quantityType.description: Amount of substance is a standards-defined quantity that measures the size of an ensemble of elementary entities, such as atoms, molecules, electrons, and other particles. It is sometimes referred to as chemical amount. The SI unit for this quantity is the mole (mol). @see Wikipedia: Amount of Substance

quantityType.name: quantity
quantityType.description: Quantity of something whole otherwise without unit. ie. Count of engine starts, loads, dumps.

quantityType.name: latitude
quantityType.description: The angular distance of a place north or south of the earth's equator, or of a celestial object north or south of the celestial equator, usually expressed in degrees and minutes. The SI unit for this quantity is degrees (rad). @see Wikipedia: Latitude

quantityType.name: longitude
quantityType.description: The angular distance of a place east or west of the meridian at Greenwich, England, or west of the standard meridian of a celestial object, usually expressed in degrees and minutes. The SI unit for this quantity is degrees (rad). @see Wikipedia: Longitude

quantityType.name: angle
quantityType.description: In planar geometry, an angle is the figure formed by two rays, called the sides of the angle, sharing a common endpoint, called the vertex of the angle. The SI unit for this quantity is radian (rad). @see Wikipedia: Angle

quantityType.name: angular acceleration
angular speed
area
quantityType.description: Area is the quantity that expresses the extent of a two-dimensional figure or shape, or planar lamina, in the plane. The SI unit for this quantity is square metre (m2). @see Wikipedia: Area

quantityType.name: unitless
load
quantityType.description: Loads of material.

quantityType.name: load rate
quantityType.description: Loads of material per time period.

quantityType.name: electric capacitance
electric charge
quantityType.description: Electric charge is the physical property of matter that causes it to experience a force when placed in an electromagnetic field. The SI unit for this quantity is Coulomb (C). @see Wikipedia: Electric Charge

quantityType.name: electric conductance
electric current
electric inductance
quantityType.description: Electric inductance is the property of a conductor by which a change in current flowing through it induces (creates) a voltage (electromotive force) in both the conductor itself (self-inductance) and in any nearby conductors (mutual inductance). The SI unit for this quantity is Henry (H). @see Wikipedia: Inductance

quantityType.name: electric potential
quantityType.description: Electric potential is the amount of electric potential energy that a unitary point electric charge would have if located at any point of space, and is equal to the work done by an electric field in carrying a unit positive charge from infinity to that point. The SI unit for this quantity is Volt (V). @see Wikipedia: Electric Potential

quantityType.name: electric resistance
quantityType.description: Electric resistance of an electrical conductor is the opposition to the passage of an electric current through that conductor. The SI unit for this quantity is Ohm (Î©). @see Wikipedia: Electric Resistance

quantityType.name: energy
force
frequency
illuminance
length
luminous flux
luminous intensity
quantityType.description: Luminous Intensity is a measure of the wavelength-weighted power emitted by a light source in a particular direction per unit solid angle, based on the luminosity function, a standardized model of the sensitivity of the human eye. The SI unit for this quantity is candela (cd). @see Wikipedia: Luminous Intensity

quantityType.name: magnetic flux
quantityType.description: The Magnetic flux through a surface is the surface integral of the normal component of the magnetic field B passing through that surface. The SI unit for this quantity is weber (Wb). @see Wikipedia: Magnetic Flux

quantityType.name: magnetic flux density
mass
quantityType.description: Mass is a property of a physical body which determines the strength of its mutual gravitational attraction to other bodies, its resistance to being accelerated by a force, and in the theory of relativity gives the mass-energy content of a system. The SI unit for this quantity is kilogram (kg). @see Wikipedia: Mass

quantityType.name: mass flow rate
power
pressure
quantityType.description: Pressure is the force applied perpendicular to the surface of an object per unit area over which that force is distributed. The SI unit for this quantity is Pascal (Pa). @see Wikipedia: Power

quantityType.name: radioactivity
solid angle
quantityType.description: Solid Angle is the two-dimensional angle in three-dimensional space that an object subtends at a point. The SI unit for this quantity is steradian (sr). @see Wikipedia: Radioactivity

quantityType.name: speed
storage
quantityType.description: A unit of Information is the capacity of some standard data storage system or communication channel, used to measure the capacities of other systems and channels. The SI unit for this quantity is bit (b). @see Wikipedia: Units of Information

quantityType.name: temperature
time
torque
viscosity
quantityType.description: The viscosity of a fluid is a measure of its resistance to gradual deformation by shear stress or tensile stress. The SI unit for this quantity is pascal-second (Pa.s). @see Wikipedia: Viscosity

quantityType.name: volume
quantityType.description: Volume is the quantity of three-dimensional space enclosed by some closed boundary that a solid substance occupies. The SI unit for this quantity is cubic metre (m3). @see Wikipedia: Volume

quantityType.name: liquid volume
quantityType.description: Liquid Volume is the quantity of three-dimensional space enclosed by some closed boundary for a liquid substance. The SI unit for this quantity is litre (l).

quantityType.name: volumetric flow rate
bank volume
bank volume flow rate
quantityType.description: Flow rates for bank volumes

quantityType.name: loose volume
quantityType.description: A measure of material after being disturbed by blasting and loading. @see Glossary: Loose Cubic Meters

quantityType.name: loose volume flow rate
quantityType.description: Flow rates for loose volumes
